Angioedema
Angioedema is sudden puffiness (swelling), often of the skin. It can happen:
• On your face or privates (genitals).
• In your belly (abdomen) or other body parts.
It usually happens quickly and gets better in 1 or 2 days. It often starts at night and is found when you wake up. You may get red, itchy patches of skin (hives). Attacks can be dangerous if your breathing passages get puffy.
The condition may happen only once, or it can come back at random times. It may happen for several years before it goes away for good.
HOME CARE
• Only take medicines as told by your doctor.
• Always carry your emergency allergy medicines with you.
• Wear a medical bracelet as told by your doctor.
• Avoid things that you know will cause attacks (triggers).
GET HELP IF:
• You have another attack.
• Your attacks happen more often or get worse.
• The condition was passed to you by your parents and you want to have children.
GET HELP RIGHT AWAY IF:
• Your mouth, tongue, or lips are very puffy.
• You have trouble breathing.
• You have trouble swallowing.
• You pass out (faint).
MAKE SURE YOU:
• Understand these instructions.
• Will watch your condition.
• Will get help right away if you are not doing well or get worse.
